00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:01.550
State of the Union.

00:00:01.550 --> 00:00:06.240
It's been one year since I last
stood up here and talked about how

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:07.380
Apple is doing in the enterprise.

00:00:07.380 --> 00:00:10.420
And boy, it's been an incredible year.

00:00:10.420 --> 00:00:15.170
We've had an increasing product
line aimed at the enterprise.

00:00:15.290 --> 00:00:20.540
We've had very aggressive adoption
by our partners and some great

00:00:20.540 --> 00:00:25.820
feedback from our customers and
from the industry in general.

00:00:26.820 --> 00:00:30.320
To start out, I'd just like to give you
a little feel for that.

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:34.020
Here's a quote from P.J.

00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:37.150
Conloy in InfoWorld.

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:40.300
And this touches on a
very interesting subject.

00:00:40.300 --> 00:00:44.810
The combination of the cluster node
configuration and X-Grid clustering

00:00:44.810 --> 00:00:51.310
software represents a revolution in how
IT looks at computers and builds systems.

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:54.860
And if those of you
who remember last year,

00:00:54.860 --> 00:01:00.040
I mentioned that we were... We were going
to first see clustering in academia,

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:03.760
but the very same things that
were driving clustering and

00:01:04.060 --> 00:01:07.660
its use in research were going
to find their way into IT.

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:11.840
And Apple jumped ahead of the
curve there and jumped right into

00:01:11.860 --> 00:01:14.520
clustering in academia and science.

00:01:14.600 --> 00:01:15.290
And guess what?

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:20.230
We're starting to see it in
the IT shops as we speak.

00:01:20.350 --> 00:01:24.310
I'll talk a little bit more
about that as we go on.

00:01:24.340 --> 00:01:26.780
Another quote from
Tom Yeager at InfoWorld.

00:01:26.780 --> 00:01:30.500
If you want a complete
productivity platform,

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:33.600
you can nickel and dime
your way there with Windows.

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:36.540
Actually,
I think nickels and dimes are probably

00:01:36.540 --> 00:01:38.740
too small a denomination for that.

00:01:38.770 --> 00:01:42.310
You can hammer and saw
your way there with Linux.

00:01:42.470 --> 00:01:46.020
And for anyone who has deployed
Linux in the enterprise,

00:01:46.020 --> 00:01:49.350
I'm sure you know what I mean
by hammers and saws or what

00:01:49.470 --> 00:01:51.580
Tom means by hammers and saws.

00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:55.540
Or you can hit the
ground running with OS X.

00:01:55.540 --> 00:01:58.770
And that is... That is really
the key differentiator.

00:01:58.780 --> 00:02:03.780
I mean, OS X, if you look at it,
is chock full of open source software,

00:02:03.780 --> 00:02:07.270
runs a lot of open source tools,
as you would in Linux.

00:02:07.410 --> 00:02:11.710
But the big difference is that Apple,
we take the responsibility

00:02:11.710 --> 00:02:14.570
for integration,
for QA, for testing,

00:02:14.570 --> 00:02:16.300
for security updates.

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:19.540
We give you a way to
hit the ground running,

00:02:19.670 --> 00:02:22.000
so it's kind of the best of both worlds.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.700
You get the support you would
get from a proprietary system,

00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:29.460
but the full power of taking
advantage of the world's ability

00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:35.700
to create open source software
with all of that available on OS X.

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:43.150
Just an incredibly increasing number
of enterprise customers over the

00:02:43.150 --> 00:02:46.200
last year actually in deployment.

00:02:46.220 --> 00:02:49.700
And we're going to actually hear
from some of those guys later today.

00:02:49.700 --> 00:02:52.880
They'll kind of take you through
their decision process and

00:02:53.030 --> 00:02:54.700
where they are in that process.

00:02:54.700 --> 00:02:57.590
I think you'll find
that very interesting.

00:02:57.870 --> 00:03:00.300
So, innovation.

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:02.650
You heard about this
from Steve this morning.

00:03:02.650 --> 00:03:07.300
If Apple is anything,
Apple is an innovative company.

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:11.080
I think we almost stand for
innovation in our industry.

00:03:11.080 --> 00:03:14.760
And you hear about innovation
a lot in terms of the

00:03:14.770 --> 00:03:17.330
consumer side of our business.

00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:20.500
So the iPod or the iTunes music
store and what we've done to

00:03:20.500 --> 00:03:22.460
the music industry in general.

00:03:23.460 --> 00:03:29.370
Or iLife and the consumer
products that we make available.

00:03:29.980 --> 00:03:34.460
However, innovation also translates
into the world of IT.

00:03:34.460 --> 00:03:38.060
And in the world of IT,
it's not just innovation

00:03:38.060 --> 00:03:41.460
around ease of use,
