00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:06.350
Finally, or one more story that's of
interest and sort of centers

00:18:06.350 --> 00:18:14.800
around not just 24/7 availability,
is the army.mil website.

00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:19.400
It's actually about 60 different
websites that the Army runs and these

00:18:19.400 --> 00:18:22.400
are deployed on XSERVs and XSERV raids.

00:18:22.540 --> 00:18:26.400
The interesting thing about this is,
as you can imagine,

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:32.400
these sites get attacked
occasionally by hackers.

00:18:32.400 --> 00:18:36.560
And they've been running
these sites on Mac OS X since,

00:18:36.740 --> 00:18:42.280
for about the last five years and
the result is no successful attacks.

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:47.220
So not only do they have a site that
just stays up and keeps running,

00:18:47.470 --> 00:18:51.370
but there have been no successful
hacker attacks on this site.

00:18:51.400 --> 00:18:57.400
The other interesting thing is that
they serve over a terabyte per day.

00:18:57.650 --> 00:19:00.400
This is not just a static website.

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:02.400
They actually make
heavy use of streaming.

00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:08.400
And Apple has a lot of great server-side
products for quick time streaming.

00:19:08.400 --> 00:19:11.400
That's part of their solution.

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:14.320
And so this is a very heavy traffic site.

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:18.000
It's a heavy amount of
bits streaming out of it,

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.400
getting hacked all the time.

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:22.400
It just keeps on running.

00:19:22.400 --> 00:19:31.170
So a great example of Macs being deployed
into a very mission-critical environment.

00:19:31.430 --> 00:19:33.050
This one is fun.

00:19:33.060 --> 00:19:35.960
This is UCLA physics and
astronomy department.

00:19:35.960 --> 00:19:43.290
These examples just keep coming up
of clusters getting deployed of max.

00:19:43.490 --> 00:19:49.660
Clusters of 64, 128, 256,
1024 clusters of max.

00:19:49.730 --> 00:19:53.400
It turns out to be just a great solution.

00:19:53.400 --> 00:19:59.680
In this case, they're using it,
they've got 256 dual processor

00:19:59.770 --> 00:20:04.370
XSERVs and the result is they can
do 4 trillion double precision

00:20:04.490 --> 00:20:06.050
floating point operations per second.

00:20:06.060 --> 00:20:12.560
They use this to do fusion research
at UCLA and one of the most fun things

00:20:12.560 --> 00:20:19.010
whenever one of these gets deployed is,
especially in a university environment,

00:20:19.090 --> 00:20:22.780
is when everyone sort of gets
together to assemble the thing.

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:23.380
And this is a very interesting example.

00:20:23.380 --> 00:20:26.860
And in this case,
they did some time lapse movies and put

00:20:26.860 --> 00:20:31.500
together a little film showing it kind
of getting built from the ground up.

00:20:31.500 --> 00:20:35.950
And I thought I would just share
that with you because it's kind of a,

00:20:36.040 --> 00:20:37.410
it's fun to watch.

