00:35:31.120 --> 00:35:34.250
standards really rings true here.

00:35:34.740 --> 00:35:43.160
Next I'd like to introduce Joe Duemel
from Aozora Bank and he's the

00:35:43.160 --> 00:35:45.300
joint general manager there.

00:35:45.300 --> 00:35:46.300
Joe Duemel: Hi, this is Dan.

00:35:46.300 --> 00:35:49.300
This is a bank.

00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:54.940
This is a more typical IT enterprise
shop and he would like to share

00:35:54.940 --> 00:36:01.300
with you some of his experience with
Apple and with Mac and ideas about

00:36:01.300 --> 00:36:03.270
open source and open standards.

00:36:03.300 --> 00:36:09.380
So Joe, welcome.

00:36:11.610 --> 00:36:14.720
So I'm sure the first question you have,
since you're probably not up to

00:36:14.730 --> 00:36:17.920
date on all your Japanese banks,
is what is Azora Bank?

00:36:17.960 --> 00:36:23.000
Azora Bank is a successful and
profitable bank in downtown Tokyo.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:27.030
They're primarily a commercial
and special finance bank.

00:36:27.040 --> 00:36:30.980
Azora recently turned
over its management team.

00:36:30.980 --> 00:36:33.150
And as part of that,
we looked at the challenge

00:36:33.260 --> 00:36:36.340
of how do we manage systems,
technology and people that were

00:36:36.400 --> 00:36:38.520
relatively stuck in the 1990s.

00:36:39.640 --> 00:36:43.020
Like some of the other presenters,
I also have everything in my data center.

00:36:43.020 --> 00:36:45.240
I have stacks of IBMs.

00:36:45.240 --> 00:36:47.950
I have the old tape drives
you see on old sci-fi movies.

00:36:47.980 --> 00:36:51.120
I have a pretty scary data center.

00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:54.520
The room that you're looking
at there is a tape library.

00:36:54.520 --> 00:36:56.280
It's a robotic tape library.

00:36:56.280 --> 00:36:58.420
It manages a whole 1.2 terabyte of data.

00:37:01.730 --> 00:37:04.850
Got a little robot in there,
zips back and forth.

00:37:04.850 --> 00:37:08.540
It was replaced by something
that looks about that high.

00:37:08.770 --> 00:37:09.740
We have a new management team.

00:37:09.740 --> 00:37:13.220
Part of the charter of the new management
team is they wanted to create an

00:37:13.220 --> 00:37:15.940
environment of knowledge workers.

00:37:15.950 --> 00:37:18.980
They wanted to get rid of
a paper-based environment.

00:37:18.980 --> 00:37:22.720
They wanted to be an energetic or genki,
is the Japanese word for it, bank.

00:37:22.720 --> 00:37:25.890
They brought us on board and we
looked at this thing and we said,

00:37:25.980 --> 00:37:28.190
okay, we don't want to deploy Windows.

00:37:35.060 --> 00:37:38.230
So we started with some rules
and the first rule is it's got

00:37:38.250 --> 00:37:40.760
to contribute to good karma.

00:37:40.760 --> 00:37:44.660
And nobody gets good karma with Windows.

00:37:44.780 --> 00:37:47.110
We also discovered that we were
really building from the ground up.

00:37:47.190 --> 00:37:49.680
As we started this process, we thought,
okay, you know,

00:37:49.680 --> 00:37:52.080
we'll replace the desktops, put,
you know, maybe some Linux in the

00:37:52.080 --> 00:37:53.190
back end and we'll be fine.

00:37:53.200 --> 00:37:55.760
We started looking at replacing
the desktops and discovered we

00:37:55.880 --> 00:37:57.270
needed to upgrade our network.

00:37:57.340 --> 00:37:59.890
Okay, I found out I had hubs
underneath the floors.

00:37:59.900 --> 00:38:01.540
I wouldn't have put them there,
but that's okay.

00:38:01.540 --> 00:38:04.660
We pull up the floors,
we look at the floors, we're like, okay,

00:38:04.660 --> 00:38:06.020
we need a full recable.

00:38:06.020 --> 00:38:10.260
We start the recable effort, we say,
okay, now I need new switches.

00:38:10.260 --> 00:38:12.920
It's time to go to Cisco,
get all new switches, do this right,

00:38:12.940 --> 00:38:14.020
because I don't want to do it again.

00:38:14.780 --> 00:38:16.660
As we did that,
we looked at our power requirements.

00:38:16.700 --> 00:38:20.330
I didn't have enough power per
floor to run my Cisco switches.

00:38:20.380 --> 00:38:23.190
So I said, okay,
we went to our power distribution

00:38:23.190 --> 00:38:27.380
and we upgraded that and they said,
well, you know, you only got about five,

00:38:27.380 --> 00:38:28.410
ten minutes of UPS.

00:38:28.420 --> 00:38:30.640
Okay, that doesn't really work either.

00:38:30.640 --> 00:38:33.970
We started pouring concrete
in the basement to put in new

00:38:33.970 --> 00:38:37.520
UPSs so that we could put in
the power distribution units,

00:38:37.630 --> 00:38:40.660
so we could put in the switches,
so we could build a data center.

00:38:42.220 --> 00:38:43.460
Fundamentally,
what we're looking at doing

00:38:43.460 --> 00:38:44.760
is creating an IT revolution.

00:38:44.800 --> 00:38:48.300
We were going to replace
every single desktop unit.

00:38:48.300 --> 00:38:52.000
We were going to take the 75
different vendors in our data center,

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:53.920
consolidate them down to maybe four.

00:38:53.920 --> 00:38:56.600
We were going to streamline
our systems and processes,

00:38:56.600 --> 00:38:59.240
make it a manageable thing,
get rid of access databases

00:38:59.270 --> 00:39:02.620
and Excel spreadsheets,
holding customer information, etc.

00:39:02.620 --> 00:39:06.040
So as we sat down and discussed it,
we decided we needed some rules.

00:39:06.090 --> 00:39:08.410
The first rule was education.

00:39:08.460 --> 00:39:12.540
We did not want to end up
being beholden to any vendor.

00:39:12.630 --> 00:39:14.140
We wanted to own our own environment.

00:39:14.140 --> 00:39:16.300
All our employees,
all the guys who run the

00:39:16.300 --> 00:39:17.740
stuff daily are Japanese.

00:39:17.740 --> 00:39:19.650
You know, when you deal with a U.S.

00:39:19.770 --> 00:39:23.080
vendor, you have to make sure that
you have the right education.

00:39:23.130 --> 00:39:25.040
So we made education
a very high priority.

00:39:25.190 --> 00:39:29.130
We wanted our people
to run their systems.

00:39:29.390 --> 00:39:39.320
Design Design was really important to us.

00:39:39.420 --> 00:39:43.460
Design of the work environment,
design of the systems environment,

00:39:43.700 --> 00:39:45.000
design of the business processes.

00:39:45.040 --> 00:39:49.080
Design was important to get right because
without it we were back to the bad

00:39:49.090 --> 00:39:52.060
karma thing and it wasn't looking good.

00:39:52.060 --> 00:39:54.990
Partnership We knew that
we couldn't do this alone.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:58.140
We knew that we had to go
to the industry leaders,

00:39:58.140 --> 00:40:01.680
people like Apple, people like Cisco,
people like EMC Documentum,

00:40:01.680 --> 00:40:03.820
people like TIBCO for integration.

00:40:03.820 --> 00:40:05.810
We needed this stuff to work
and we needed to go to the

00:40:05.810 --> 00:40:08.300
people who knew it best.

00:40:08.300 --> 00:40:10.960
So as you look at this,
this is a pretty big IT investment.

00:40:10.970 --> 00:40:14.720
We're spending $30,
$40 million trying to get this

00:40:14.720 --> 00:40:16.580
right and that's just the first cut.

00:40:16.580 --> 00:40:18.030
So we wanted to do it right.

00:40:18.170 --> 00:40:20.640
We knew that partnership was
going to be really important.

00:40:20.640 --> 00:40:22.350
More rules.

00:40:22.750 --> 00:40:24.740
First thing about partners,
they have to be an innovation leader.

00:40:24.740 --> 00:40:27.160
They have to own their space.

00:40:27.170 --> 00:40:29.870
When you mention their name,
people have to go, yeah, networking,

00:40:29.900 --> 00:40:30.420
they got it.

00:40:30.490 --> 00:40:33.530
Apple, yeah, desktops, they got it.

00:40:33.530 --> 00:40:37.600
They have to train our people
in their intellectual property.

00:40:37.600 --> 00:40:40.880
Again, one of the things that really
broke earlier was that it was

00:40:40.930 --> 00:40:44.100
really hard to separate our
people from the vendor armies that

00:40:44.100 --> 00:40:46.040
kept giving me consulting bills.

00:40:46.060 --> 00:40:49.260
So it was important for me to
actually really own my enterprise.

00:40:50.800 --> 00:40:51.800
Mutual non-disclosure.

00:40:51.800 --> 00:40:55.500
As you work in any of these partnerships,
you find that you need to

00:40:55.630 --> 00:40:56.980
plan ahead five to ten years.

00:40:56.980 --> 00:40:59.480
Planning ahead five to ten years
means you need to know what your

00:40:59.480 --> 00:41:02.290
vendors are going to do and they
need to know what you're going to do.

00:41:02.350 --> 00:41:04.610
So mutual non-disclosure
became really important to us.

00:41:04.620 --> 00:41:07.160
And the last one is
executive level sponsorship.

00:41:07.250 --> 00:41:10.970
As you do a partnership like this,
whether it's a partnership with Apple,

00:41:11.120 --> 00:41:13.680
partnership with Cisco,
stuff's going to go wrong.

00:41:13.780 --> 00:41:15.600
It's not all perfect, it never is.

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:18.120
It's important to be able
to go to someone and say,

00:41:18.120 --> 00:41:20.130
hey, look, help me make this work.

00:41:20.240 --> 00:41:20.580
And share an idea with them.

00:41:20.580 --> 00:41:20.620
And share an idea with them.

00:41:20.620 --> 00:41:23.620
on both our successes and our problems.

00:41:24.710 --> 00:41:28.180
So, as I described this to our management
committee and as we worked together,

00:41:28.180 --> 00:41:30.800
the question we kept hearing was,
why Apple?

00:41:30.800 --> 00:41:33.670
The answer we thought was really clear.

00:41:33.670 --> 00:41:37.460
Undeniably, they're the leader in
the field in innovation,

00:41:37.550 --> 00:41:41.000
both hardware, software,
both for the enterprise and the desktop.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:42.930
They really had it.

00:41:43.830 --> 00:41:46.260
The second was access to the
best and brightest minds.

00:41:46.260 --> 00:41:49.780
It was really important to us to
be able to go to the people at

00:41:49.800 --> 00:41:53.420
Apple that make things work and go,
how do I do this here?

00:41:53.460 --> 00:41:55.560
Because it doesn't make sense.

00:41:55.560 --> 00:41:58.920
One of the things we looked at
is as we were trying to pull

00:41:59.010 --> 00:42:03.480
all our systems together is,
you know, okay, I got Java, I got Unix,

00:42:03.480 --> 00:42:06.980
I got 3270,
I've got some legacy Windows stuff

00:42:06.990 --> 00:42:10.290
that runs in terminal servers,
I've got X Windows,

00:42:10.290 --> 00:42:12.010
how do I make it work?

00:42:12.080 --> 00:42:13.710
The nice thing with OS X?

00:42:13.810 --> 00:42:14.870
It all just works.

00:42:14.880 --> 00:42:17.110
Don't have to do a whole lot
different to make it work.

00:42:17.160 --> 00:42:18.640
Highly internationalized.

00:42:18.770 --> 00:42:21.520
My kanji's really bad.

00:42:21.540 --> 00:42:25.360
I'm really happy that I can
flip into an English screen.

00:42:25.360 --> 00:42:28.780
A lot of the Japanese employees
are really happy that I'm not

00:42:28.780 --> 00:42:30.320
trapping them in an English screen.

00:42:30.320 --> 00:42:34.050
The fact that OS X is
internationalized from the ground up,

00:42:34.110 --> 00:42:37.150
that Apple is built with a view
towards being internationalized,

00:42:37.150 --> 00:42:38.710
is critically important to us.

00:42:38.740 --> 00:42:43.490
And Apple's really energetic,
and that was real important.

00:42:45.180 --> 00:42:49.860
So I told you earlier I was going to
show you what our employees work at.

00:42:49.860 --> 00:42:53.770
Basically everybody has their very own
three and a half feet of linear space,

00:42:54.150 --> 00:42:57.420
which they share with whatever
books and coffee cups they

00:42:57.520 --> 00:42:58.740
want to put on their desk.

00:42:58.740 --> 00:43:02.080
They sit next to each other.

00:43:02.460 --> 00:43:06.620
They're separated by a file cabinet.

00:43:07.320 --> 00:43:09.800
This is not a knowledge
worker environment.

00:43:09.800 --> 00:43:09.800
So we destroyed it.

00:43:10.420 --> 00:43:13.540
and David Right now I have
20 floors in my headquarters,

00:43:13.540 --> 00:43:18.240
I have six floors in my data center
and I'm progressively destroying

00:43:18.240 --> 00:43:21.740
it floor by floor and replacing it.

00:43:21.740 --> 00:43:23.400
Here's what we're replacing it with.

00:43:23.400 --> 00:43:26.360
This is prior to our first rollout.

00:43:30.540 --> 00:43:33.520
One of the scarier sites
I've ever seen in my life,

00:43:33.630 --> 00:43:38.100
every one of those ended up
VESA mounted in cubicles.

00:43:38.100 --> 00:43:40.850
And as you VESA mounted them,
you take the old stand off.

00:43:40.850 --> 00:43:44.300
We stacked the stands from one
side of the floor to the other.

00:43:44.300 --> 00:43:46.160
It was kind of interesting.

00:43:47.180 --> 00:43:49.600
So some of the challenges
we're looking at.

00:43:49.680 --> 00:43:50.540
We're a bank.

00:43:50.660 --> 00:43:53.000
We are legally responsible for
our customers' information.

00:43:53.040 --> 00:43:57.430
It's very important in Japan that
customer information never get out.

00:43:57.480 --> 00:44:00.920
We don't quite get the same option that
they might have in the US as saying,

00:44:00.920 --> 00:44:04.890
"Oops, I lost it." You say, "Oops,
I lost it." They say,

00:44:04.910 --> 00:44:09.980
"You lost your banking
license." My management says,

00:44:09.980 --> 00:44:09.980
"That's bad."

00:44:10.770 --> 00:44:12.190
We have a high need of integration.

00:44:12.200 --> 00:44:14.200
I mean, we do have a bunch of systems.

00:44:14.320 --> 00:44:17.080
When we first looked at this,
we were going to use Mac on the desktop,

00:44:17.230 --> 00:44:18.280
not in the server room.

00:44:18.280 --> 00:44:21.050
We had to get this stuff working.

00:44:21.050 --> 00:44:22.890
I have tons of paper on every floor.

00:44:23.020 --> 00:44:26.300
We're actually lightening our
building's earthquake load because

00:44:26.300 --> 00:44:30.010
we're moving the paper into Documentum,
which gets backed up into big, you know,

00:44:30.070 --> 00:44:32.110
terabytes and terabytes of storage, etc.

00:44:32.110 --> 00:44:36.070
But I needed to make Documentum, TIBCO,
Oracle, everything work right.

00:44:36.100 --> 00:44:39.940
When we started this process,
it didn't all work on Apple.

00:44:39.990 --> 00:44:44.490
So we had to go to TIBCO and say, "Hey,
we need some help." TIBCO responded.

00:44:44.490 --> 00:44:45.660
They worked with Apple.

00:44:45.740 --> 00:44:47.240
Apple and TIBCO got together.

00:44:47.270 --> 00:44:50.460
They got together a beta version
of their messaging product,

00:44:50.600 --> 00:44:53.560
their system management tool
and I'm pretty happy to say that

00:44:53.560 --> 00:44:55.110
they're now generally available.

00:44:55.110 --> 00:44:57.760
They've been released,
which means I can run them in production,

00:44:57.760 --> 00:44:58.760
which is a good thing.

00:44:58.790 --> 00:45:00.770
Also,
they've also--TIBCO is also committed

00:45:00.780 --> 00:45:04.920
to porting the rest of their product
stack to OS X by the end of the year,

00:45:04.920 --> 00:45:07.780
so that really helps me as well.

00:45:09.090 --> 00:45:11.160
So the question I get asked
from the Apple people is

00:45:11.180 --> 00:45:12.880
when are you going to Tiger?

00:45:12.940 --> 00:45:13.800
So I'm kind of weird.

00:45:13.800 --> 00:45:16.600
My management asked me
why I'm going to Apple,

00:45:16.600 --> 00:45:17.580
why Apple?

00:45:17.640 --> 00:45:19.140
Apple asked me when am I going to Tiger?

00:45:19.140 --> 00:45:20.830
The answer is I started out on Tiger.

00:45:20.880 --> 00:45:21.620
I had no choice.

00:45:21.620 --> 00:45:26.210
Tiger has the only security
model that would work.

00:45:26.210 --> 00:45:30.590
All my clients are net
boot with encrypted swap.

00:45:30.590 --> 00:45:35.490
I do not have any customer
data on any disk on the floor.

00:45:35.490 --> 00:45:35.870
To me that was absolutely critical.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:39.490
It's that banking license thing.

00:45:39.500 --> 00:45:40.630
They seem to care.

00:45:40.630 --> 00:45:43.500
The second thing is card services.

00:45:43.500 --> 00:45:44.910
My security model is pretty tight.

00:45:44.920 --> 00:45:48.300
It's a combination of what you have,
which is your physical key card,

00:45:48.430 --> 00:45:51.500
and what you know,
which is your password.

00:45:51.500 --> 00:45:53.790
So basically that key card also
controls the ability to come

00:45:53.860 --> 00:45:54.870
in and out of the building.

00:45:54.910 --> 00:45:57.620
If you go to the restroom,
you pull out the key card.

00:45:57.620 --> 00:46:00.290
The Mac flips using,
I think at the moment it's a

00:46:00.290 --> 00:46:02.740
user switch to a screen saver.

00:46:02.740 --> 00:46:07.760
You go to the bathroom, come back in,
plug it back in, you're back in.

00:46:07.780 --> 00:46:08.500
The next thing is the ACLs.

00:46:08.600 --> 00:46:09.600
You've kind of heard a lot from them.

00:46:09.600 --> 00:46:10.780
They were critical for us.

00:46:10.780 --> 00:46:13.180
I do full role-based authentication.

00:46:13.180 --> 00:46:15.510
I know when anybody touches any data.

00:46:15.560 --> 00:46:19.510
And I really needed the ACLs and
client lockdown based on roles.

00:46:19.550 --> 00:46:22.730
The other thing that really,
really hit us is manageability.

00:46:22.980 --> 00:46:25.050
Tokyo real estate is a little expensive.

00:46:25.080 --> 00:46:28.240
It was important for me to be able
to put my help desk out in Fuchu.

00:46:28.310 --> 00:46:31.110
Fuchu is our data center,
about 30 kilometers,

00:46:31.110 --> 00:46:33.430
maybe 40 kilometers outside of Tokyo.

00:46:33.680 --> 00:46:37.510
But I had executives and
executives need help.

00:46:40.390 --> 00:46:42.850
It was important that my help desk
guys could help my executives.

